  <!-- Page 2: Single linear equation -->
  <page>
    <title>A Single Linear Equation</title>

    <p>
      A linear equation has the form:
    </p>
    <p workspace="1.5in">
      <m>\begin{aligned}
        a_1 x_1 + a_2 x_2 + \cdots + a_n x_n = b
      \end{aligned}</m>
    </p>

    <p workspace="1in">
      Here, <m>a_1,\dotsc,a_n</m> and <m>b</m> are the <em>coefficients</em>, <m>x_1,\dotsc,x_n</m> are the
      <em>variables</em> (unknowns), and <m>n</m> is the <em>dimension</em> (number of variables).
    </p>

    <p workspace="2in">
      Examples:
      <ul>
        <li><m>2x_1+4x_2=4</m> is a line in two dimensions.</li>
        <li><m>3x_1+2x_2+x_3=6</m> is a plane in three dimensions.</li>
      </ul>
    </p>
  </page>

  <!-- Page 3: Systems of linear equations + definition -->
  <page>
    <title>Systems of Linear Equations</title>

    <p>
      A <em>linear system</em> consists of multiple linear equations in the same variables. For example:
    </p>

    <p workspace="2in">
      <m>\begin{aligned}
        x_1 \amp\;+\; 1.5\,x_2 \;+\; \pi x_3 \;=\; 4 \\
        5x_1 \amp\;+\; \phantom{1.5\,x_2}\;+\; 7x_3 \;=\; 5
      \end{aligned}</m>
    </p>

    <definition>
      <title>Solution to a Linear System</title>
      <p workspace="1.5in">
        The set of all values of <m>x_1, x_2, \ldots, x_n</m> that satisfy <em>every</em> equation in the system.
      </p>
    </definition>

    <p workspace="1in">
      A system can have a unique solution, no solution, or infinitely many solutions.
    </p>
  </page>

