  <!-- Page 5: Three-dimensional case -->
  <page>
    <title>Three-Dimensional Case</title>

    <p>
      An equation <m>a_1x_1+a_2x_2+a_3x_3=b</m> defines a plane in <m>\mathbb{R}^3</m>.
      For three equations, the solution set is the intersection of three planes.
    </p>

    <p workspace="2in">
      For each possible solution set, sketch and state the number of solutions:
    </p>

    <p workspace="2.5in">
      <strong>Line:</strong> intersection of two non-parallel planes with the third also intersecting along that line.
      <br/>Number of solutions: ____________
    </p>

    <p workspace="2.5in">
      <strong>Point:</strong> three planes intersect at a single point.
      <br/>Number of solutions: ____________
    </p>

    <p workspace="2.5in">
      <strong>Empty:</strong> no common intersection (e.g., parallel or inconsistent planes).
      <br/>Number of solutions: ____________
    </p>
  </page>

  <!-- Page 6: Row operations -->
  <page>
    <title>Row Reduction by Elementary Row Operations</title>

    <p>
      To solve a linear system, we use <em>row operations</em> on the augmented matrix:
    </p>
    <p workspace="1.5in">
      <ol>
        <li><strong>Replacement/Addition:</strong> add a multiple of one row to another.</li>
        <li><strong>Interchange:</strong> swap two rows.</li>
        <li><strong>Scaling:</strong> multiply a row by a nonzero scalar.</li>
      </ol>
    </p>

    <p workspace="2.5in">
      Apply these operations to systematically simplify the matrix to an equivalent (easier to read) form.
      Explain each step as you go.
    </p>
  </page>

