  <!-- Page 8: Augmented matrices -->
  <page>
    <title>Augmented Matrices</title>

    <p>
      It’s redundant to write variables repeatedly; we use an augmented matrix to encode the system.
    </p>

    <p>
      Original system:
    </p>
    <p workspace="1.5in">
      <m>\begin{aligned}
        x_1 - 2x_2 + x_3 \amp= 0 \\
        \phantom{x_1 - 2x_2 +}\; 2x_2 - 8x_3 \amp= 8 \\
        5x_1 - 5x_3 \amp= 10
      \end{aligned}</m>
    </p>

    <p>
      Augmented matrix:
    </p>
    <p workspace="2in">
      <m>\left[\begin{array}{ccc|c}
        1 \amp -2 \amp 1 \amp 0 \\
        0 \amp 2 \amp -8 \amp 8 \\
        5 \amp 0 \amp -5 \amp 10
      \end{array}\right]</m>
    </p>

    <p workspace="1.5in">
      The vertical bar separates the coefficient matrix (for <m>x_1,x_2,x_3</m>) from the constants.
    </p>
  </page>

  <!-- Page 9: Consistency + Row equivalence (fill-in definitions) -->
  <page>
    <title>Consistent Systems and Row Equivalence</title>

    <definition>
      <title>Consistent</title>
      <p workspace="1.5in">
        A linear system is <em>consistent</em> if it has at least one
        <m>\underline{\phantom{\,\,solution\,\,}}</m>.
      </p>
    </definition>

    <definition>
      <title>Row Equivalence</title>
      <p workspace="2in">
        Two matrices are <em>row equivalent</em> if a sequence of
        <m>\underline{\phantom{\,\,elementary row operations\,\,}}</m>
        transforms one matrix into the other.
      </p>
    </definition>

    <p workspace="1.5in">
      Note: If the augmented matrices of two linear systems are row equivalent, they have the same solution set.
    </p>
  </page>

